Our target is called SalePrice. First, we can fit a simple regression model consisting of only the intercept (the average of SalePrice). Fit the model and then use the broom package to

** NOTE : ** not answered. Not sure how to define a model which has just the intercept.

Now fit a linear regression model using GrLivArea, OverallQual, and Neighborhood as the features. Don’t forget to look at data_description.txt to understand what these variables mean. Ask yourself these questions before fitting the model:

  • What kind of relationship will these features have with our target? OverallQual and Neighborhood should have a direct impact on the final saleprice. However, GrLiveArea might not be.

  • Can the relationship be estimated linearly? Yes, we can extablish a linear relationship.

  • Are these good features, given the problem we are trying to solve? Yes, OverallQual and Neighborhood are good feature. But, GrLivArea might not be.

#### After fitting the model, output the coefficients and the R-squared using the broom package

model <- lm(formula = SalePrice ~ OverallQual + Neighborhood + GrLivArea, data = trainData)

  • How would you interpret the coefficients on GrLivArea and OverallQual? When everything else (features) is constant. Increase in one square feet area in “GrLivArea”, “SalePrice” increases by $55.5645. Similarly, when everything else is (features) constant, an increase in 1 unit of “OverallQual” increases “SalePrice” by $20951.

  • How would you interpret the coefficient on NeighborhoodBrkSide? Neighborhood coefficients are relative to “Bloomington Heights” of Ames city. So, compared to “Bloomington Heights”, SalePrice in “Brookside” are $13025.45 less.

  • Are the features significant? Yes, these features are significant. The p.value for all the features are near to Zero.

  • Are the features practically significant? They are practically significiant. However, except GrLivArea. one square feet change in “GrLivArea” affects the saleprice by only $55.56.

  • Is the model a good fit? No, model doesn’t consider other features like “YearBuilt”, “HouseStyle”, “LotArea” and many more.

One downside of the linear model is that it is sensitive to unusual values because the distance incorporates a squared term. Fit a linear model to the simulated data below (use y as the target and x as the feature), and look at the resulting coefficients and R-squared. Rerun it about 5-6 times to generate different simulated datasets. What do you notice about the model’s coefficient on x and the R-squared values?

sim1a <- tibble(x = rep(1:10, each = 3), y = x * 1.5 + 6 + rt(length(x), df = 2))
model <- lm(formula = y ~ x, data = sim1a)
tidy(model)
